The compiler is thought to be an African3 he was a contemporary of Facundus, Bishop of Hermaeum, and just as Facundus wrote very eagerly in behalf of Theodore of Mopsuestia, this compiler wrote very strongly in defence of Theodoret. His prin- cipal material was a curious and extensive collec- tion of documents and Letters made by Count Irenaeus, Bishop of Tyre, after the Council of Ephesus 3 it contains Letters that passed between the different Bishops in the Province of Antioch about Nestorius and S.
